# CursorBlame — Project Overview & Architecture

CursorBlame is a VS Code / Cursor **extension** that displays inline git blame annotations on the active cursor line.
Hovering reveals a tooltip with commit details and a clickable link to open the commit on the remote host (GitHub, GitLab, Bitbucket, Azure DevOps).

## Repository layout

```
src/
  extension.ts    – Entry point: activation lifecycle, event wiring, commands, workspace trust
  gitBlame.ts     – git blame execution (execFile) and --line-porcelain parser
  blameCache.ts   – Per-file LRU cache keyed by filePath::gitHead, invalidated on save / HEAD change
  decoration.ts   – TextEditorDecorationType "after" overlay, hover message with command-link
  remoteUrl.ts    – Remote provider detection, SSH/git→https normalisation, commit URL construction
  types.ts        – Shared TypeScript interfaces (BlameInfo, FileBlameMap, RemoteInfo, BlameConfig, RemoteProvider)
images/
  icon.png        – Extension marketplace icon (128×128)
dist/
  extension.js    – Production bundle (esbuild output, do NOT edit)
esbuild.js       – Build script (CommonJS, bundles src/ → dist/extension.js, externals: vscode)
package.json     – Extension manifest: commands, keybindings, contributes.configuration schema
tsconfig.json    – Strict TypeScript config (ES2020, CommonJS)
```

## Key technical decisions

- **Build tool**: esbuild (fast bundling, CJS output, `vscode` externalised).
- **Target**: Node 16 / ES2020, VS Code engine ≥ 1.75.
- **No test framework yet** — changes are verified with `npm run typecheck` and manual F5 testing.
- **Activation**: `onStartupFinished` — the extension activates lazily after the editor is ready.
- **Workspace trust**: the extension is disabled in untrusted workspaces and only activates once trust is granted.

## Development workflow

| Command                     | Purpose                                 |
|-----------------------------|-----------------------------------------|
| `npm run watch`             | Incremental dev build (esbuild --watch) |
| `npm run build`             | One-shot dev build with source maps     |
| `npm run typecheck`         | Strict `tsc --noEmit`                   |
| `npm run vscode:prepublish` | Production build (minified, no maps)    |
| `npm run package`           | Create `.vsix` via `vsce`               |

## Commit messages

Follow [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/):

```
<type>(<scope>): <summary>
```

Types: `feat`, `fix`, `perf`, `refactor`, `docs`, `chore`, `ci`.
Scope matches a module name: `extension`, `gitBlame`, `blameCache`, `decoration`, `remoteUrl`, `types`.

## Module dependency graph (import direction →)

```
extension.ts → blameCache.ts → types.ts
extension.ts → decoration.ts → remoteUrl.ts → types.ts
extension.ts → gitBlame.ts   → types.ts
extension.ts → remoteUrl.ts  → gitBlame.ts (isValidSha only)
```

`types.ts` has zero imports — it is the leaf of the dependency tree.
Do NOT introduce circular dependencies.
